        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/test-samples",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test samples acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Physical test samples (pump impellers and housings) are manufactured to drawing tolerances and dimensionally inspected. CMM reports confirm all critical dimensions within ±0.05 mm of nominal."
      },
      "rationale": "Test samples are dimensionally verified against the CAD geometry used in the CFD model. Dimensional correspondence is confirmed by CMM inspection, ensuring the validation experiments are representative of the simulated geometry."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equiv-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "The equivalency of input parameters factor addresses whether the computational model inputs are equivalent to the physical test inputs when validation is performed on a surrogate or analogous device rather than the exact COU device. In this assessment, the validation experiments were conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry used in the COU simulations, with the same blood analog fluid and the same operating conditions. Because there is no surrogate-to-COU translation required — the validation and COU domains are coincident — a formal equivalency mapping exercise would be circular and adds no credibility information. ASME V&V 40 Table 3 guidance for MRL 2 does not mandate this factor when the validation domain is identical to the COU domain. The factor is therefore scoped out as not applicable to this specific assessment configuration, consistent with the rationale that scoping decisions must be documented and technically justified."
    }
